segments.text: November the 4th, and I am talking to Dr. Chris.
Today is November the 4th.
I'm visiting with Dr. Chris Borman, who's the associate dean for the College of Education and has been at Texas A&M since 1960?
1970, which was a year after the College of Education became a college.
And Chris, one of the things that I think I would like your perceptions on, and again,
It's strictly your own feelings and where you've been, and you've been department head, professor, and now as dean.
You've seen this college evolve from the very beginning, and you've seen a lot of changes.
And what I would like is how you have perceived these changes.
What were the things that affected it or impacted the tremendous growth of the College of Education since your arrival in 1970?
Let's see.
I don't know.
These aren't in order of importance.
I would say the first thing is the university in 1970, everybody knows this, but it was probably about 13,000 students.
And I don't think anybody, certainly I didn't have the idea that I was taking a position at a university that was going to grow so rapidly.
And this was the first
college position, the only college position I've had.
Who recruited you?
Art Roach, Dr. Arthur Roach, who was at the time head of the Department of Educational Psychology.
And he recruited me.
He had gone to a summer seminar at Indiana University that was being led by my chair up there.
They were looking for somebody who had experience in vocational education and was in counseling, because they had a grant from the Texas Education Agency to train vocational counselors.
So they needed somebody who had this background in vocational education, and I had worked at a vocational high school in Hammond, Indiana for a lot of years, so I had that experience.
He started calling around and he called my chair at Indiana and he told me about it.

The thing that's kind of interesting I think is about two or three months, a couple months ahead of that, I'd been at the APGA, which is the National Counselors Association meeting in New Orleans and they have a job bank or interview type thing and I had just really
worked real hard and had maybe 13 to 15 interviews and met all these different people and Dr. Roach and several faculty members were there interviewing for this job and I never met them at all.
And then I get back to Indiana and he calls me so I came down here.
But anyway, I would say that the tremendous growth of the university, I certainly didn't have any idea that the university that I was taking a job at would go
The other thing that's kind of interesting is the job that I took was a one-year temporary job, and I'm still there.
Was it soft money?
It was soft money.
It was soft money.
They had a grant from the Texas Education Agency, and it was soft money.
And they couldn't guarantee absolutely, but Dean Hubert told me, he said that he would pretty much give his word that they would make it a permanent position, which they did the next year.
But so that... Was there very much going on with soft money at the time?
Because I have heard that, you know, he really preferred not to put too much emphasis on soft money type programs.
He wanted to have the hard... Well, I think he wanted to have the hard line position, but he was very much in favor of getting external funding.
Okay.
And he, especially at that time, vocational education money was, there was quite a bit of money available during the 70s and... Mm-hmm.
this money was a part of it.
So he was very interested in doing that.
But he did give me his word that he would try to make it a permanent position next year.
And you came into the Department of Educational Psychology, which is where you still are teaching.
Right, right.
So the size, the way the university grew.
I guess the other thing that really amazed me is the way the physical appearance of the university has changed.
I mean, you know, just the buildings and size and everything.
We were, you know, my first office was up on the fourth floor of Academic, and we had these big wooden bookcases.
I mean, it was a classroom that was made into a series of offices, and just bookcases divided us, you know.
We moved around several times.
We moved over then to Bolton Hall and had offices up there on the second or third floor.
And Harrington was a parking lot for academic at that time.
And so it was really exciting when they started building Harrington and then I think we moved in in what, 72 or 73, something like that.
The physical appearance, not that I didn't think it was an attractive campus, but they had really changed it.
Was there a lot of resistance?
I was looking at some yearbooks that had pictures and some complaints and demonstrations by students because they were putting in so much concrete and taking off some of the trees and some of this.
A&M has really strived to keep the campus, the aesthetic.
I think they have done a pretty good job of doing that.
In fact, I think they've improved it a lot.
But there was a time there during the 70s, 71, 72, where they just tore up the walks and everything, and you couldn't even, you know, there wasn't any place to walk.
I remember we were in Bolton, and they just tore up one afternoon, they just tore up the sidewalk all the way, and there was just a trench there.
And as long as it was dry, but then when it rained, it was just, I mean, it was horrible.
You couldn't even get up to the steps to get up to the, you know, and they didn't seem to have a whole lot of concern for that, you know, they just,

just kinda but what they've done I think the other thing that happened to is when I got there I came there for an interview like on a Friday I arrived on a Thursday night and I was there just for Friday and then I went back Friday evening so it was a real quick trip and between that time and the time that I accepted the job and I
I started then in the first of June teaching summer school.
And my family was still in Indiana because we had a cellar house and all that.
So it was about six weeks before they moved in.
I started teaching summer school.
And at that time is when General Rudder had died.
President Rudder had died.
So I never was on campus.
I think he was ill in the hospital at the time I was there being interviewed.
He died in March, I believe.
Oh, had he died in March?
Well, no way.
Well, he either had died or died in that interim right there.
But anyway, then General Ludeke was acting president for a year or so.
But I think another thing that is just my perception, and I think it had a significant impact on the college and on the university, was bringing Jack Williams in.
Lots and lots of changes occurred.
during his 70s.
And I think his leadership style and the way he did it is he didn't irritate.
You were talking about people being upset because they were tearing up the campus and changing things.
There are a lot of significant changes.
I mean, if you look at what's happened at A&M just since 1970, lots and lots of changes and it certainly could have upset a lot of former students, but I don't think there was a whole lot of that.
I may be naive about this and wasn't in on, you know, all the feelings there, but I think his leadership style and what happened, he was the right man for the time.
I think also having a background in history and coming from a different background, he added a flavor to the university that we needed.
Also, it's my perception that he was extremely well liked by the faculty.
The faculty had lots of respect for him.
So I think that's a significant thing.
So you have worked then under Williams as president.
You did not have any experience with Rutter.
Miller and now Vanderbilt.
I have not really, we have not discussed presidents with any of the other interviews, but that is definitely a part of the external environment, which I will be looking at.
So this is good to get these perceptions about the leadership in the university, because I've been focusing on the leadership
in the college, but it's important to get this feeling of what was going on outside of the College of Education.
And if you can expand that then to the other two administrations.
I would say just if I looked at all the administrations, I would rate his as number one.

I mean, maybe I shouldn't do that, but I would say I was really impressed with his leadership style and the growth and the way he handled it and some of the people that he had around him and everything.
I would say that he probably had the most respect of any of the, not that the other ones didn't have as much respect.
Miller wasn't in there long enough to really get an impact.
He was more, a more traditional approach to, and I think that was quite a contrast between Williams and what had gone on before.
I didn't have a
And Miller was an A&M graduate.
Do you think that had any effect?
Oh, yeah, I think it did.
I think it had an effect in that he was a background in agriculture, ag economics, and so on.
I don't think there's anything wrong with supporting all the traditions and being real strong with that, but I think that in terms of being a broad university, I think that
What has been the impact, do you think, of Vander?
He has been here now for... Well, I think five or maybe six years.
It was in 81, I guess.
Yeah, okay.
Well, he had a couple, their initial first couple years were pretty rocky, I think.
And I've been impressed with him.
Not that I've
met him and interacted with him that often.
But I have interacted with him.
And I'm impressed with him.
He's a brilliant person.
And he makes a real good impression for the community or wherever.
I mean, he's quite a scholar.
And he's an interesting person.
I don't think he has a contact with the faculty that, let's say, Jack Williams did.
What about, what has he done, in your opinion, to help the College of Education?
Is there anything specific that has happened in the College of Education because of his leadership?
Well, I think that there are a number of things.
For one thing, and this is university-wide, but I think it's had quite an impact.
I would say probably one of the biggest things then, and as I think about it now, maybe he's had more contact or impact with the faculty
Maybe I want to retract that statement.
But he, under his administration, he formed the Faculty Senate.
And there's a lot more faculty involvement, a lot more of a democratic process, and a lot more input from faculty.
And I would say that's a very strong, very strong point.
Is the faculty as a whole was very receptive to this title?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah.
I think so.
Do they have these kinds of things in most universities, these faculty centers or faculty input?
Yes, yes.
And A&M was, you know, more, I guess, because of its military background and the way it's emerged, especially since it's become so large just in the more recent years.
What is the size of the faculty now?
I'd say it's probably around 2,000.
I think that's just a rough estimate.
What is the total faculty in the College of Education?
Well, I'd say about 150, probably about 110 regular faculty positions, but probably when you count sophomore positions and everything else.
Okay.
So we talked then a little bit about the things that have affected change.

To what extent do you feel that the college, because the mission of the College of Education is the same as it is for the university or the land grant institution, which is teaching and research and service,
Under the two administrations in the College of Education, has there been a shift in emphasis between these three, or have they been given equal priority or whatever?
What is your feeling on those?
I don't see a major shift there.
I don't think that we're as, and probably you would find this with a lot of colleges of education, we're
strong on research as let's say a college of science or some of the other colleges.

I mean there isn't, it's important and people are expected to do research but I would also, you know some places there's such a strong emphasis on research and even though they say teaching is important it doesn't get as much emphasis.
And I would say it's probably more equal in our college.
And I have not really seen a big change between the Hubert administration or the Corrigan administration in terms of emphasis.
Would you rate, is it a one, two, three on teaching, research, and service in that order, possibly?
Or would it one and two be together, the teaching and the research?
I think that they want strong teachers.
But I don't think that in terms of tenure and promotion,
that you're today going to be tenuring or promoting somebody if it's just strictly teaching.
You've got to be doing some research, too.
All right.
What about you have always been, even though you're in the administrative end of it now, you also have maintained that contact with students through your teaching.
Has this tremendous growth affected how you've been able to work with students?
Have your classes changed dramatically because of these
No, I haven't really found them to change too much because I don't teach any undergraduate courses, and I never have.
The ed psych department is primarily a graduate department, and we teach some undergraduate service courses, but usually I have not taught those.
So the classes haven't, in terms of science, haven't changed.
One thing I would say, though, that the
quality of students has changed tremendously in terms of graduate students.
Because when we first started our graduate programs, and this varies from department to department, but I'm just talking about Ed's site now.
We had some pretty good students, but we had a lot of local students.
And it wasn't as competitive to get into the department
And I would say in the last five to six years it's become very, very competitive, especially since our doctoral program in counseling psychology has been accredited by the APA.
You know, they get some hundred applications a year and maybe admit ten people into their doctoral program.
And now they have an APA-accredited school psychology program, and that's the same way.
So the students, the competitiveness and the quality of the students has increased quite a bit.
Can you share a little bit about your role as department head?
How many years were you department head?
Five years.
For five years.
I'm just now starting to interview the department heads, and I don't know exactly what
What responsibilities does the department head have versus being a professor, or now that you are a dean, how would you compare those?
Well, I think that the department heads are responsible to the dean, but there's a lot of autonomy.
The department head's job, for instance, if you compare it with my current job, there's a lot of difference.
Because even though you report to the dean and you're a part of the college, there's still a lot of autonomy.
You develop the budget.
You're responsible for hiring and tenure and promotion.
Even though you have faculty committees and the dean advising you or working with you on it, the decisions and responsibility decisions are the department head's.
And I didn't really realize.
Well, I think I did an adequate job as department head, but I didn't realize how much was involved in it until I got into it.
Do they allow special compensation?
How are department heads compensated for the extra work?
There is not a special percentage that you get extra for being a department head.
But they usually, in terms of salary, they usually give you a little bit bigger raise so that you're one of the better paid people.
Do they adjust your teaching load as well?
Oh, yes.
On department head, like I, I would only be teaching one third time.
And that's the same way with being in the dean's office.
Now that you're in the dean's office and you sort of are looking from a different window, how do you see
Within the College of Education, the collaborative effort among departments, you were part of one department that works evidently with several others.
How much of that goes on in the college, this collaborative?
Not as much as I'd like to say.
Why and what can be done about it?
I don't know.
Well, I do know some reasons, I guess.
I'm not saying that there isn't collaboration.
There is.
And I think that when Dean Corrigan came, and one of the things he was very instrumental in getting the faculty to initiate was the inquiry process.
And that is supposed to be promoting collaboration.
It does promote it to a certain extent.
But to me, there still isn't as much collaboration.
And I'm talking about not just between departments, but I'm also talking collaboration between faculty within departments.
I think that one of the things that has caused our faculty to be kind of independent and on their own is our evaluation process.
I think that...
to, in terms of tenure promotion and salary increase, they're going to look at your teaching, but they're also going to look at how many articles you've published and these kinds of things.
And I think that the main thing the faculty want to do
is get their couple articles out.
And I'm being a little trite here, and I don't mean that.
But they want to get some quick article, do a little research, get some articles out, and get them published.
And as long as my vita looks fine, that's what I need to do.
And I think faculty do want to do collaboration, but they want some assurances that they're going to get adequate credit when it comes to evaluation each year.
And so I'm not saying that there isn't collaboration, but I think we could do a lot better than we're doing.
And would it require changing the evaluation process?
Oh, yeah, yeah.
Is that even feasible or possible?
Yes, I think it's feasible.
I don't see it happening, but I think it's feasible.
One of the comments that one person made to me was that they would like to see departments just done away with and have just one college where you, because there's so much
Not just exactly turf protection, but also the department has, and being that you were one, probably you can relate to this, having to fight, so to speak, for the resources for their department.
And that sort of prevents what you're just saying, the collaboration, because everybody has to look out for their own.
Yeah, our colleges, if you look at colleges of education across the country, is organized in a fairly traditional way.
And what I'm saying about not being enough collaboration and kind of everybody doing their own thing is not unusual.
It happens.
I mean, when we were working out how to set up this school-university collaborative organization, we visited a number of different universities and major universities, too.
And it's going on at other places, too.
Can you tell me a little bit about the school-university collaborative?
Because I understand that's a brand new endeavor that is going to have some very
Well, we've been working on this for several years, and the one person I've been working very closely with in particular is Jim McNamara.

And what got me involved in this or interested in this was I was getting feedback from faculty who were saying, I want to get into the schools to do research, and it's really difficult to get into the schools and do research.
We need some help.
And one faculty member in Ed Psych gave me a paper that was presented at an AERA conference on
a collaborative organization they had at the University of Illinois, how there was an office and this woman kind of brokered research projects in the schools and everything.
So we started looking at what we could do and we visited Illinois and Indiana and some other places like that.
What evolved in a very quick way is that last January, January of 87,
We had a day and a half conference in the Woodlands.
And we selected eight school districts who we thought would be ideal school districts to work with.
And the other thing, the other side of the coin is faculty are saying they want to get into schools and do research.

But if you talk to teachers in the school, there's schools that are saying, well, I'm not sure if I want to work with these faculty in the College of Education because they're not doing research that's relevant or that's going to have an effect on what I'm doing in the classroom.
So what we want to do is we want to get
faculty and teachers together in the public schools and develop some joint research projects and some collaborative, cooperative type activities to encourage research.
And so we had this conference and we selected eight school districts.
And then we got them, asked them to make a commitment for the next year to kind of on a cooperative way, experimental way, to see if we can develop this organization.
And they've developed a research project now that they're working on.
They're collecting data on dropouts in all eight districts.
And they're trying to analyze or collect data on the characteristics of dropouts.
The next step then is that that would lead to intervention strategies and so on.
And we've also come up with a plan for formalizing the organization.
And we're planning a second annual conference, a school-university collaborative conference in the Woodlands in January.
And we're going to ask each school district to formally join the organization.
We're also asking these eight school districts to invite another school district.
And this is going to be known, I think, as the Texas A&M School-University Collaborative Research Consortium.
I think that's it.
So I'm excited about it.
And who picked this particular area for research?
Was it the university, or was it the schools, or was it done jointly?
It was kind of done jointly, but I would say primarily the schools.
We wanted to do something that was more action-oriented that they felt that they needed.
These things that you're doing now that you're talking about are going to influence the perceptions of how outsiders view the College of Education, obviously.
Not that that's the ulterior motive that you're doing it, but it will help.
How is that perception right now within the state for the College of Education from outside Texas A&M?
I would think that it is very good.
When we started in the 70s, we were not one of the major teacher education institutions in the state.
And I would say today we are recognized as
Either they are one of the major teacher education institutions in the state.
Turning out more teachers, I think, than almost any other state institution.
And also I think the quality, the quality of the students we're attracting and the students that we're turning out.
And I try to say this in an objective way, but I think we're way out there.
And I think also, I think in the state we have excellent visibility.
I think that nationally we have visibility because of our dean and maybe a few faculty who are well-known because of the research or writing that they've done.
And I think that we're also known because of the visibility of our dean because he's had a lot of national offices.
And he's on the executive committee, the Holmes group.
He has a lot of visibility.
And he came here with
having certainly two deanships before this one.
So I think that that's it.
I don't think we have as much visibility as the talent that's there.
I think we have visibility.
I think we have outstanding visibility in the state.
I think we have visibility nationally, but I think it's just because of a few people.
And I think that we're kind of hiding our talent under a
a basket or something, or whatever you want to say.

I think that we need to get some, and I think this is where I would talk about collaboration between faculty, and of course one of my jobs is external funding, and I guess I'm a little frustrated at times, but I think that the quality of the people that we have, that if we could get them to work together a little bit more, whereas we could get a couple national research centers here, or
some really major projects, research projects, I think we would have that visibility.
For instance, the University of Illinois has had the National Center for Reading that's funded by the US Department of Education.
It's had it there for 10 or 15 years.
And I think overall, the quality of the faculty that we have compared with Illinois is very comparable.
But because they've had this center and this visibility, I think that that's made a big difference.
And we've got an outstanding reading faculty at EDCI, and they're really top people.
So anyway.
OK.
Probably one of the things that I want to talk about a little bit is the future and what you see the College of Education at Texas A&M achieving in the, say, 21st century, the year 2000.
I know there has been a study about the year 2000.
